Briefly to sum up, Aristotle's collection ol facts was often inade- quate either in number or character to form a basis ol induction‚ his method was osten unscientific, his ideas were often vague and indis- tinct, and his fundamental maxims and distinctions were generally preconceived and assumed rather than gathered from experience and reasoningtt
